If a farmer can trade four chickens for a pig, three pigs for two sheep, and five sheep for two cows, what is the minimum number of cows he needs to trade for $20$ chickens?
}

\textbf{Answer:} We can multiply the quantity of $20$ chickens by the conversion factors from the problem to change the units from chickens to cows:$$20\ \text{chickens} \cdot \frac{1\ \text{pig}}{4\ \text{chickens}} \cdot \frac{2 \ \text{sheep}}{3\ \text{pigs}} \cdot \frac{2\ \text{cows}}{5\ \text{sheep}}=\frac{4}{3}\ \text{cows}.$$Hence the farmer needs at least $\boxed{2}$ cows.
